In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims April as National Cancer Control Month. He highlights the progress made in the fight against cancer, but acknowledges that it remains the second leading cause of death in the United States. The President emphasizes the importance of taking action to reduce the risk of developing cancer, such as not smoking, maintaining a healthy diet, exercising regularly, and limiting alcohol consumption and sun exposure. He also mentions the efforts made to make cancer screenings more accessible and affordable through the Affordable Care Act. Additionally, the President encourages individuals to seek information on cancer prevention from sources such as BeTobaccoFree.gov, SmokeFree.gov, and Cancer.gov. He mentions the investment in medical research to better understand and combat cancer. The proclamation calls for renewed efforts to defeat cancer, honor those who have passed away, support survivors, and bring hope to those battling the disease.